a "wonderful raconteur.? The nonphilosophical highlight of the book is Cohen's remarkable account of his first trip to India, which includes unforgettable vignettes of encounters with strangers and reflections on poverty and begging. Other biographical pieces include his valedictory lecture at Oxford, in which he describes his philosophical development and offers his impressions of other philosophers, and "Isaiah's Marx, and Mine," a tribute to his mentor Isaiah Berlin. Other essays address such topics as the truth in "small-c conservatism," who can and can't condemn terrorists, and the essence of bullshit. A recurring theme is finding completion in relation to the world of other human beings. Engaging, perceptive, and empathetic, these writings reveal a more personal side of one of the most influential philosophers of our time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aPhilosopherszGreat Britain. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066258008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045953140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400845323zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400845323.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-045953-1  Princeton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066258-0  PUP eBook-Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aP